[1] Brazil (Mato Grosso do Sul)
Date: Fri 4 Dec 2009
Source: Midiamax [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.midiamax.com/view.php?mat_id=590499>


The number of dengue cases in November of this year [2009] has
greatly increased, and there is now an epidemic situation, according
to information from the coordinator of Health Surveillance, Ana Lucia
Lyrio de Oliveira. In November 2009, 481 dengue cases were recorded,
whereas in this same period last year [2008], the number was 110.
During the entire last year [2008], there were 1800 dengue cases,
whereas in 2009, the recorded cases reached 2500.

According to the coordinator, an epidemic situation is reached when
the number of expected cases is surpassed. The expected quantity of
expected reported cases is 250, and this number was almost doubled in
November this year [2009]. A comparison [of November] with the month
of October 2009 also shows a considerable increase in the number of
cases, with the number that month [being] 181 cases. The reason for
the increase in November 2009 cases is related to climate factors and
the return of [dengue virus] serotype 1, which came from Bolivia,
stated the coordinator.

"An epidemic is when there is a greater number of cases than
expected. What hurt [this November 2009] was the hot weather combined
with the frequent rains, leaving an environment conducive to the
spread of the disease [reproduction of the dengue virus vector
mosquito]. Furthermore, we had a return of [dengue virus] serotype 1,
which increased the cases also, showing that people are [the
population is] more susceptible," said the coordinator.

Another problem pointed out by the coordinator is the lack of public
awareness, and the public, despite [information] campaigns, continues
to act negligently on the issue [of vector control]. The region
causing the greatest concern is the eastern region, which includes
the Taruma, Coophavilla, and part of Aero Rancho neighborhoods. In
order to contain the number of cases, joint efforts are being made
with vehicles for fumigation.

"There are people who are unaware [of mosquito breeding]; this
results in a person creating [mosquito] breeding sites for an entire
neighborhood, so now we are making joint efforts to fumigate with
vehicles. But use of these vehicles shows that dengue is spreading,
because we are combating the adult insect and not the larvae," stated
the Coordinator.

In November [2009], (health) Minister Jose Gomes Temporao said in
Campo Grande that Mato Grosso do Sul will be included in a program to
combat dengue. He came to the capital to launch the campaign "Brazil
United Against Dengue." According to him, up to December [2009], R
1.02 billion [USD 586 million] will be appropriated to combat dengue
in the state.

From January-August of this year [2009], 12 441 cases of the disease
[dengue] were reported, triple the number reported for the same
period last year [2008], when 4065 cases were reported. The state is
moving in the opposite direction of the country, since the number of
cases here in the state tripled, while the in rest of the country,
the disease fell by 79.2 percent compared to the period from January
to August last year [2008].

According to the Ministry of Health, the [dengue] situation is
critical in 7 cities of Mato Grosso do Sul: Bonito, Campo Grande,
Corumba, Coxim, Dourados, Ponta Pora, and Tres Lagoas.

[Byline: Paulo Xavier]

